NAPPY CHANGE or Olympic sport? 
So there's a few things no one tells you about being a parent before you become a parent including how hard breastfeeding is, how hard it is to get your baby to "sleep through" and that your child will have developed super human strength by the time they turn 1 and when he/she doesn't want to do something such as nappy change time it becomes like a workout just trying to get it done. So, I'm here to tell you any mamas to be or even mums of sweet little newborns who are yet to gain that super human strength that you must come prepared for when the time comes! 
My tips for an easier nappy change: 
1. DISTRACTION: practice your audition for "The voice" and sing to them, give them an iPad , dummy, toys , keys or anything that will distract them for long enough to get them to lay down. Next baby I'm going to install a TV on the roof maybe ?? 💁🏽
2. BE ORGANISED: have the nappy , wipe and cream (if needed) laid out and ready to go before you start. All with in arms reach - because safety first and you only have moments to get this done because at any moment small super human child will flip over and stand up (as pictured) or just kick you in the face. 
3. OUT & ABOUT: make sure you have your nappy bag sufficiently stocked up before leaving home with nappies, wipes, cream, disposable nappy bags, hand sanitiser (because poooo can happen anywhere and you may need to resorting to nappy changes in the back of car or middle of park) , change mat and distraction tools. There's nothing worse than getting caught out in public with a poo explosion and having to ask a random for a nappy (yep, has happened to me including once on a plane where the air host asked over the loud speaker - 🤦🏽‍♀️ bad mum moment) .... and if all else fails hit the gym to work on your strength to combat their strength , hire a nanny or pass the buck to Daddy (dreaming) ! ✌🏽
Let me know your tips!!!

Ships from the Republic of Singapore navy, Royal Thai navy and U.S. Navy completed a three-day multilateral Cooperation Afloat Readiness and Training (CARAT) exercise in the South China Sea May 12.

The three-day exercise included a broad spectrum of naval competencies and maritime security training aimed at enhancing cooperation and interoperability amongst the three navies. 
The Formidable-class frigate RSS Intrepid (FFS 69) represented the Republic of Singapore navy at sea, and the Naresuan-class frigate HTMS Naresuan (FFG 421) participated from the Royal Thai navy. Participating U.S. ships included the Arleigh Burke class guided-missile destroyer USS Sterett (DDG 104) and the littoral combat ship USS Coronado (LCS 4). While operating together at sea the ships completed a robust schedule including divisional tactic maneuvers; visit, board, search and seizure training; joint flight operations; and communications drills.
